How R is a bit broken when you install it

Sometimes you need to help yourself.

You will likely need to define startup options

â€œR is so mathy that it is hard to interact withâ€: stringsAsFactors

If you create an R dataframe, it will assume that your string entry is a factor.

â€œ#> invalid factor level, NA generatedâ€

options(stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

â€œWho likes scientific notation?â€: scientific notation penalty

All numeric output comes as scientific notation.

Itâ€™s running the default, which limits you to 5 digits.
options(scipen = NULL) 
print(100000)
## [1] 1e+05
options(scipen = 999)
print(100000)
## [1] 100000

What you want as your startup file

These are worthy of:

    1. being in your .RProfile or
    1. In an sourced-in script that you cite before all of your programs or
    1. just throw them at the top of your scripts
options(stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
options(scipen = 999)

Whatâ€™s a .RProfile?

Your .Rprofile is an R script that runs each time R runs and they can be found within R_HOME, HOME and the projectâ€™s home directory.
Find them with getwd().

R and speed

It really can go fast, you may just have to change a few things.

â€œCan I really use a for loop?â€

What are you doing? The answer is usually YES, unless you have enormous, artificial, and staged tasks.
R does structural checks on its data. It evaluates columns each time you change a dataframe. This can be slow for huge output datasets.
- Create a full object structure (i.e., a blank dataframe) then update it rather than appending to it.

â€œI run out of RAM using Râ€

tidyverse functions donâ€™t â€œmodify in place,â€ they copy and then (once verified as good) delete the old. This takes 2x the space! Use a totally different package, like data.table, that is built for speed and modifies in place.

â€œAre there better versions of R?â€ (yes, there are)

Vanilla R is the slowest R. It assumes your CPU has no math coprocessing. Matrix manipulations cannot get slower.
a - Speed up your processing. Try Microsoft R Open for BLAS (basic linear algebra subprograms) + Intel math kernel libraries. Other BLAS packs (OpenBLAS for general CPUs, NVBLAS for NVidia GPUs) are available too.

b - Speed up your data structures. data.table has a lot of efficiency tweaks.

c - Speed up your data IO. Big data solutions that abstract from/with R: Spark, RevolutionR/ScaleR/MRS/AzureR/Rocker/H2O.

d - all of the above. Use MRO with data.table. Data IO is constantly changing, but can offer significant improvements.

e - â€œfutureâ€ package (in development now) for de-serializing programs (or doParallel or foreach).

One last sectionâ€¦.â€œI gave up on R because it made me angryâ€

Donâ€™t hit it with an ax yet. Things are already better.

For Windows non-admin installations, install to â€œC:" (or similar, NOT Program Files) or you are entering a world of pain.

â€œR isnâ€™t performing the function correctly!â€ â€œIt ran yesterday.â€

Be explicit about which libraryâ€™s function you want!

Do this: data1 %>% dplyr::select(col1)
Not this: data1 %>% select(col1)

Code breaks when two loaded packages share a function name.

6,601 results for functions named â€œselectâ€
https://www.rdocumentation.org/search?q=select&latest=1

R has improved since 2016!

Rstudio V1.x
- Accidentally printing a huge output will no longer crash/cause issues
- No longer freezes, job queuing is improved in RStudio 1.2
- Lots of added features (environment windows, connections, console, etc)

tidyverse (now one library) has taken over.
Forget about the first package suggested by Google. Get the first package suggested by rstudio. It will likely be tidyverse.

Lots of improvements to applying functions to data at scale
apply functions are still neato, but you can iterate and use lists better than ever (purrr, broom, etc)

New and useful for time series data: tsibble

dRive in style. Be capable, fast, and frustration-free!

Summary

  • A few lines of startup code can truly help.
  • A few packages remove pain points and create simpler operation.
  • There are a range of ways to make R faster. It is worth evaluating which are best for your situation.
  • RStudio has been doing a great job of refining R.
